  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (synthetic adversarial)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). Validation results report R-squared and Pearson correlation of predicted versus measured shear-stress distributions across the pump impeller passages, which characterise how well the model tracks the spatial pattern of wall shear stress. These metrics are presented as the primary evidence that the model is fit for the COU; however, the COU question of interest is whether the model correctly predicts the relative hemolysis index (RH) across five flow-speed operating points, which depends on the volumetric integral of the scalar stress-exposure history along blood-element pathlines — a quantity that can remain poorly predicted even when wall-shear-stress spatial correlation is high.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-requirement",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-claim",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-hemolysis-v2",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-piv-dataset",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-hemolysis-bench-dataset"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-shear-stress-r2",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Spatial shear-stress distribution R-squared validation",
      "description": "Predicted wall shear stress magnitudes at 312 impeller-passage measurement locations were compared against PIV-derived estimates from the FDA benchmark pump dataset at the nominal operating point (5 L/min, 2500 rpm). The coefficient of determination R² = 0.94 and Pearson correlation r = 0.97 indicate excellent agreement in the spatial pattern and relative magnitude of wall shear stress across the impeller. These statistics demonstrate that the turbulence model (SST k-ω) accurately reproduces the spatial distribution of fluid mechanical loading on the impeller walls, supporting confidence in the model's representation of flow physics. Because hemolysis is driven by shear stress experienced by red blood cells, strong agreement in shear-stress spatial distribution is considered indicative of model fidelity for hemolysis prediction. The R² and Pearson metrics are therefore reported as the primary quantitative validation evidence for this COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-vr-pressure-rise-rmse",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pump pressure-rise RMSE across operating map",
      "description": "Predicted pump pressure rise (ΔP) was compared against bench measurements at all five COU flow-speed operating points. Root-mean-square error RMSE = 4.2 mmHg (2.1% of mean measured ΔP) and mean absolute error MAE = 3.6 mmHg confirm that global hydraulic performance is well-captured. Pressure-rise accuracy is used as a secondary indicator that the bulk flow field is correctly resolved, providing corroborating evidence for the shear-stress validation. Together, the R² on shear-stress distribution and the RMSE on pressure rise are presented as sufficient quantitative validation evidence that the model is suitable for identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions."
    }
  ],
