      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must pass published benchmark verification cases for incompressible turbulent pipe flow and rotating machinery.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent passes Taylor-Couette and rotating-disk benchmark cases documented in solver verification manual. No custom solver modifications were applied. Required level 1 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be less than 5% for pressure rise and wall shear stress at the nominal operating point.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed: coarse (4.2M cells), medium (11.6M cells), fine (28.4M cells). GCI for pressure rise = 1.8%; GCI for area-averaged wall shear stress = 3.4%. Both below 5% threshold. Medium mesh selected for production runs. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match COU operating envelope within stated tolerances; fluid properties and boundary conditions must be documented.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark PIV experiments conducted at 5 L/min, 2500 rpm with water-glycerol blood analog (viscosity 3.5 mPa·s, density 1050 kg/m³). COU operating points span 3–7 L/min, 1500–3500 rpm. Nominal operating point is within the validated envelope. Boundary conditions (inlet velocity profile, outlet pressure) replicated from published experimental protocol. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative agreement metrics must be reported for at least one model output directly related to hemolysis prediction; R² ≥ 0.90 or RMSE within 10% of measured range acceptable.",
      "rationale": "R² = 0.94 for wall shear stress spatial distribution (312 measurement locations, PIV benchmark). RMSE = 4.2 mmHg for pressure rise across five operating points (2.1% of mean). Both metrics exceed acceptance thresholds. The shear-stress R² is interpreted as direct evidence of hemolysis-relevant flow-field accuracy because wall shear stress is the primary mechanical driver of red blood cell damage. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2.",
      "assessmentNote": "WEAKENER TARGET: The acceptance criterion and rationale treat R² on wall-shear-stress spatial distribution as equivalent to validation of the relative hemolysis index (RH). The COU requires prediction of RH = NIH_device/NIH_reference across five operating points, which depends on the Lagrangian integral of stress exposure along blood-element pathlines — not the Eulerian spatial correlation of wall shear stress. High R² on the wall-shear-stress field is a necessary but not sufficient condition: models with R² > 0.93 have been shown to produce RH errors exceeding 40% when pathline residence-time distributions are poorly captured. No direct comparison of predicted versus measured RH or normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values is reported."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validated quantities must be mechanistically linked to the COU quantity of interest (RH); the linkage must be explicitly documented.",
      "rationale": "Wall shear stress is the primary mechanical input to the power-law hemolysis damage accumulation model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation). High spatial correlation between predicted and measured wall shear stress (R² = 0.94) is documented as evidence that the model captures the mechanistic driver of hemolysis. The linkage from wall-shear-stress accuracy to RH prediction is stated qualitatively but not quantified through a sensitivity analysis or direct RH comparison. Achieved level 2 assessed on the basis of the documented mechanistic linkage."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted at conditions representative of the COU operating envelope and must exercise the model in its intended predictive role.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at the nominal COU operating point. Fluid properties, rotational speed, and flow rate match COU conditions within 5%. The validation activity exercises the same CFD workflow (mesh, turbulence model, boundary conditions) used for COU predictions. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
